                  <additions><!--THIS element in domlib CONTAINS ESCAPED HTML, thus it is not possible to reliably extract the information about pages. Please watch out.-->
                     <list>
                        <item xml:id="a1">
                           <locus target="#1v">Fol. 1v</locus>: Prayer.<q xml:lang="gez"/>
                           <q xml:lang="en"/>
                           The text can be used as the ʾanbǝro ʾǝd of the Anaphora of St. John the Son of Thunder and the ḫadafe näfs of the Anaphora of St. John Chrysostom. The first of these Anaphoras is absent from the Ms., the corresponding part of the second does not contain this text. The omitted text may have been written out separately.
Written in a single column.
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="a2">
                           <locus target="#2ra">Fols. 2ra-3</locus>vb: Excerpts from an unidentified liturgical text.<q xml:lang="gez">Fol. 2ra, ls.1-4: …ወጊዜ፡ መንፈቀ፡ ሌሊት፡ ጸለዩ፡ ጳውሎስ፡ ወሲላስ፡ ወሰብሕዎ፡ ለእግዚአብሔር፡… Fol. 3vb, ls.30-33: …እግዚአብሔር፡ አምላክ፡ አኃዜ፡ ኵሉ፡ አቡሁ፡ ለእግዚእነ፡ ወመድኀኒነ፡…</q>
                           <q xml:lang="en"/>
                           “Rejected leaves” originating from an older Ms., occasionally included into MR-014b. Text includes scriptural readings (Acts 16:25-34; Mt 25:1-13) as well as mentions of an ʾanbǝro ʾǝd and a creed (without the texts). Old, fine handwriting (not later than the 15th cent.). Supplication formulas mention priest Gäbrä Krǝstos (possibly the owner of the Ms. from which these folios were taken).
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="a3">
                           <locus target="#61rb">Fol. 61rb</locus>: Ownership note.<q xml:lang="gez">Fol. 61rb: ዝቅዳሴ፡ ዘቅዱስ፡ ሚካኤል፡ ዘአድሕያው፡ ዘተሣየጣ፡ በንዋዩ፡ ወዘጸሐፋ፡ አቡነ፡ ወልደ፡ ሙሴ፡ ለዓለመ፡ ዓለም፡ አሜን።</q>
                           <q xml:lang="en">Fol. 61rb: This Missal belongs to (the church of) Qǝddus Mikaʾel in ʾAdḥǝyaw. He who bought it for his own money and he who wrote it is ʾabunä Wäldä Muse, for ever and ever. Amen.</q>
                           The Ms. originates from the church of Qǝddus Mikaʾel in ʾAdḥǝyaw (ʿAd Ḥǝyaw?), but its current location is the chruch of Śǝllase Mǝdrä Ruba.
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="e1">- Fol. 1r, 1v: Crude notes, poorly visible.&#xD;
- Fol. 51v (in the upper margin): Crude note.&#xD;
- Fol. 60vb: Supplication formula mentions ʾabunä Ṣäware Mäsqäl, possibly the head of the local church community at the time of the writing of the Ms.&#xD;
- Fols. 62r, 62v: Crude notes.</item>
                     </list>
